<tr>
	<td class="alt2" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>Farsky</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Senior Member<br />
	
	<br /><img src="image.php?s=6481a19bede3d83152ca99c716da51ea&amp;userid=19082&amp;dateline=1077633786" border="0" alt="Avatar" title="Farsky's Avatar" hspace="4" vspace="4" /><br />
	<br />
	Joined: May 2002<br />
	Location: A wooden box in an old Chinese man's curio shop
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt2" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Beryllin</b><br /><i>When God created Adam and Eve, they were perfect. He walked with them in perfect fellowship.<br />
<br />
Now, there are 3 levels of human existance: The flesh, which is self-explanatory; the soul, which is the mind, the ability to think, the emotions, etc. and the spirit. Now, I'm not sure about this, but when they disobeyed God in the garden, it's my belief that the spirit was no longer alive within them from that point on.</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>I'd say there are two divisions instead of three: body and spirit.  The body entails the flesh, while the spirit is a culmination of thoughts, emotions, and what you refer to as the spirit.<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Beryllin</b><br /><i>So, because of original sin, man's body and soul are alive, but the spirit is dead. That's why Paul writes that we were 'dead in our trespasses and sins' before accepting God's salvation. Obviously, our body and soul is alive, so it must be the spirit that is dead.</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>I believe Paul is referring to our spirit being dead in a sense relative to God, not dead as in destroyed.  More that it is "dirty," or tainted from Original Sin, since the Bible pushes the idea that the sins of the father are visited upon the son.  Since the spirit still has that black mark, God will have nothing to do with it.<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Bery</b><br /><i>So, when we are saved; that is, when we receive the free gift of grace, which comes through faith, we experience a new birth; the spirit is now alive. The body is unchanged, and the soul is now free to obey God, because the spirit is alive.<br />
<br />
My point in this is to say that from the moment of that second birth, when we are born again, God no longer sees the same evil person, He sees a person who is righteous before Him, even though our flesh can still fail us. His Son has purchased our righteousness with His death and resurrection. Once that spirit is born, it's a permanent change.</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>It is indeed a permanent change, but I would argue that the ideology says that it is not through faith alone, but rather through the acceptance of Jesus as one's savior, which alters the spirit.  Not only does it clean it, but it changes it fundamentally into something else.  No matter what, the original "alpha version" of the spirit can't get to Heaven.  This new, Jesusified beta version can, though.  The flesh doesn't enter into this at all, except that it is the vehicle through which we sin (not inherently evil, rather like the gun a murderer uses).  The flesh doesn't "fail," rather the spirit does.  And it <i>will</i> fail, because of that fundamental flaw (Original Sin, if you like), no matter what.  However, this new, improved spirit been coated with non-stick spray.  Prayer and repentance is all one needs to get God to squeegee that sin right off.<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Bery</b><br /><i>There are certainly objections one can throw out to this concept.<br />
<br />
"Then after the spiritual birth, one can sin all one wants with impunity." might be such a one. However, that is not the case, your life has been purchased with blood. God will, if He needs to, take such a person home early, not to mention that we still suffer consequences here for sin.</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>The religion of Christianity creates a perfect net for itself here.  The argument of "after acceptance of Jesus, one can sin all one wants" doesn't wash, because if you <i>really</i> accepted Jesus, you wouldn't <i>want</i> to sin.  It's like a catch-22 for those who want to accept Jesus as a "get out of jail free" card, while committing acts that the church considers as "sin."  They don't let you buy eternal insurance if you're going to commit high-risk acts.<br />
<br />
Religion is all about semantics, really, but since this is what each person puts his or her eternal future at stake for, I think it's a good idea to examine those words as closely as possible.  Not arguing with you, just throwing out my ideas. <img src="images/smilies/smile.gif" border="0" alt="" title="smile" smilieid="1" /></p>
	
	
	
	
	
