<tr>
	<td class="alt2" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>Beryllin</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Senior Member<br />
	
	
	<br />
	Joined: Mar 2001<br />
	Location: Kansas, but we're not there anymore!
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt2" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Farsky</b><br /><i>I'd say there are two divisions instead of three: body and spirit. The body entails the flesh, while the spirit is a culmination of thoughts, emotions, and what you refer to as the spirit.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
I believe Paul is referring to our spirit being dead in a sense relative to God, not dead as in destroyed. More that it is "dirty," or tainted from Original Sin, since the Bible pushes the idea that the sins of the father are visited upon the son. Since the spirit still has that black mark, God will have nothing to do with it.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
It is indeed a permanent change, but I would argue that the ideology says that it is not through faith alone, but rather through the acceptance of Jesus as one's savior, which alters the spirit. Not only does it clean it, but it changes it fundamentally into something else. No matter what, the original "alpha version" of the spirit can't get to Heaven. This new, Jesusified beta version can, though. The flesh doesn't enter into this at all, except that it is the vehicle through which we sin (not inherently evil, rather like the gun a murderer uses). The flesh doesn't "fail," rather the spirit does. And it <i>will</i> fail, because of that fundamental flaw (Original Sin, if you like), no matter what. However, this new, improved spirit been coated with non-stick spray. Prayer and repentance is all one needs to get God to squeegee that sin right off.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
The religion of Christianity creates a perfect net for itself here. The argument of "after acceptance of Jesus, one can sin all one wants" doesn't wash, because if you <i>really</i> accepted Jesus, you wouldn't <i>want</i> to sin. It's like a catch-22 for those who want to accept Jesus as a "get out of jail free" card, while committing acts that the church considers as "sin." They don't let you buy eternal insurance if you're going to commit high-risk acts.<br />
<br />
Religion is all about semantics, really, but since this is what each person puts his or her eternal future at stake for, I think it's a good idea to examine those words as closely as possible. Not arguing with you, just throwing out my ideas. <img src="images/smilies/smile.gif" border="0" alt="" title="smile" smilieid="1" /></i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>I'd get my Bible out for the verses, but I'm posting from the library. Grrr. <br />
<br />
As for the soul and spirit, I can't give you a reference to book and verse from here, but a paraphrase is: "The word of God is living and as sharp as a 2 edged sword, to the dividing of the soul and spirit." Paraphrased, as I say.<br />
<br />
As for faith, I knew I was being too brief, as I said, so I left some ideas unspoken which I have said here in other threads. Yes, it is faith in the death and resurrection of Christ that gives the spirit new birth. Even so, it is not really the faith that works, but the grace of God. Think of faith as a garden hose. It is a conduit for water to a tree in the yard, but it is not the hose itself that replenishes the tree, but the water flowing through the hose. <br />
<br />
Anyway, this'll do as my response, and I'm not arguing with you, either. <img src="images/smilies/smile.gif" border="0" alt="" title="smile" smilieid="1" /><br />
 <br />
 <br />
*edit* Spelling. Grrr!!!</p>
	
	
	
	
