<tr>
	<td class="alt2" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>Khross</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Devil's Advocate to Advocatus Diaboli<br />
	
	
	<br />
	Joined: Sep 2000<br />
	Location: Dante's Inferno
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt2" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p>Montegue:<br />
<br />
Check the Von Mises Institute.<br />
<br />
Those things only happen in regulated global economies.  Completely unregulated commodities subject corporations to the laws of supply and demand.<br />
<br />
As such, value is not artificially inflated or determined by government regulation of the market.  Businesses suddenly have to earn real profits and produce real innovation and products, while the individuals in charge of the businesses are no longer free of accountability.  Since the corporation loses individual rights, the corporate board, CEO, CFO, CIO, etc. are all far less likely to engage in illegal business practices, as they would be easily found guilty of criminal action.<br />
<br />
In some cases, such as inelastic markets, the emergence of monopolies would be a good thing.  In more elastic markets, however, the laws of supply and demand would ultimately act to prevent monopolies from arising.  Competition and non-competition would benefit consumers in the appropriate arenas.<br />
<br />
For instance, in contemporary america, the minimum wage is probably the biggest offender in the artificial economy.  The minimum wage actually represents 0 net income.  In fact, given taxation and Medicare/SSI, minimum wage is probably negative net income.<br />
<br />
If you raise the minimum wage, the corresponding loss of jobs, increase in the cost of operation and product, and devaluation of actual earning value would raise also the point of negative net income to the new minimum wage.  This is truly problematic, because it compresses higher earning brackets and raises the poverty level.<br />
<br />
It also creates 0 cost labor.<br />
<br />
Conversely, if the economy is completely unregulated, labor become a markettable commodity with real world transaction value.  The economy would start to deflate from it's artificial position, restructuring economic transaction values as it deflated.  It would return the economy to a far more realistic level of interaction, while solidifying the value of labor and the human element.  Ultimately, purchasing power would start to geometrically increase, while artificial inflation disappeared.<br />
<br />
With the removal of income taxes and other earning deductions, the marginal income and economic mobility of American citizen would increase dramatically.  Since the Corporations would be forced, by new levels of personal accountability in operations, to gravitate towards environmentally and socially friendly operating methods, disincentives to production and competition would disappear, and true Supply and Demand control of a natural economy would exist, the corporations would have no reason to influence or impact government.<br />
<br />
The economy would be a self-regulating segment of society.</p>
	
	
	
		<div>__________________<br />Khross<br />
Warden of the Appropriately Confused<br />
Located Somewhere Between Limbo and Lust<br />
